wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the Plate mobile application. Explain its purpose as a cross-platform fitness class booking and management system built with Expo, React Native, and React 19. Document the architecture including Expo Router for navigation, MobX for state management, and Tailwind CSS with uniwind for styling. Describe the relationship between core components such as screens, forms, UI elements, and providers. Include implementation details of the component-driven development approach with Storybook integration. Provide practical examples of common use cases like user authentication and theme switching. Make content accessible to beginners while providing technical depth for experienced developers.

wiki_catalogs.name: ThemeProvider
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the ThemeProvider component in the Plate application. Explain its role as a React Context provider for managing dark/light theme state across the application. Document the implementation details including CSS variable injection, system theme detection via useColorScheme hook, and theme persistence mechanisms. Describe how the provider wraps the application root and makes theme state available to all consuming components. Include examples of how child components access theme context and respond to theme changes. Address common issues such as hydration mismatches between server and client, performance optimization when re-rendering on theme change, and proper integration with Expo's app lifecycle. Provide guidance on extending the provider for additional theme properties or custom theme modes.

wiki_catalogs.name: Inputs
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Inputs category of UI components in the Plate application. Explain the implementation and usage of each input component including Button, TextField, RadioGroup, ListSelect, Chip, and DarkModeSwitch. Document their props, variants, event handlers, and styling mechanisms using Tailwind CSS and uniwind. Include practical examples from the codebase showing how these components handle user interaction, form integration, and accessibility. Address cross-platform considerations for web and native, especially in components with platform-specific implementations (e.g., ListSelect.web.tsx). Highlight composition patterns such as Button with compound components and state management in controlled components. Provide troubleshooting tips for common issues like styling conflicts or event propagation.

Describe the design philosophy of separating pure UI components from business logic, enabling cross-project reusability. Include implementation details of the file structure patterns, naming conventions (PascalCase for component folders, lowercase for category folders), and export mechanisms using index.ts files. Provide practical examples from the codebase such as Button, Text, Card, and Screen components to illustrate how these patterns are applied. Address common issues related to component organization and best practices for extending the UI library while maintaining consistency.

<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: Plate Fitness Application

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
Plate is a cross-platform fitness application designed for exercise reservation and class management, supporting iOS, Android, and web platforms through Expo's universal development framework.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Provide a seamless user experience across mobile and web platforms
- Enable users to book fitness classes and manage their workout schedules
- Implement a consistent design system with dark mode support
- Facilitate social login through multiple SNS providers
- Maintain high code quality with Storybook integration for component development

### Target Audience
- Fitness enthusiasts looking to book classes
- Gym and studio administrators managing class schedules
- Mobile app developers working on cross-platform fitness applications
- UI/UX designers creating consistent component libraries

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The application follows a well-organized component architecture with clear separation of concerns:

```mermaid
graph TD
    App[Root Layout] --> Providers[Global Providers]
    Providers --> ThemeProvider[Theme Provider]
    Providers --> StateProviders[State Management]
    App --> Router[Expo Router]
    Router --> Tabs[Tabs Layout]
    Tabs --> Home[Home Screen]
    Tabs --> Explore[Explore Screen]
    Router --> Modal[Modal Screen]
    Home --> Screen[Screen Component]
    Screen --> LoginForm[Login Form]
    LoginForm --> TextField[Text Field]
    LoginForm --> Button[Button]
    Screen --> SNSButtons[SNS Buttons]
    SNSButtons --> Button
```

### Design Patterns
The project implements several key design patterns:

- **Component Composition**: Using compound components (e.g., Button with Label)
- **Provider Pattern**: Theme and state management through React Context
- **Container/Presentation Pattern**: Separation of stateful containers (LoginScreen) from presentational components (LoginScreenView)
- **Atomic Design**: Component organization follows atomic design principles with display, inputs, surfaces, and layouts
- **Feature-based Organization**: High-level features organized in dedicated directories

### System Relationships
The architecture demonstrates clear relationships between system components:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[RootLayout] --> B[Providers]
    B --> C[ThemeProvider]
    B --> D[Other Providers]
    A --> E[AppLayout]
    E --> F[Stack Navigator]
    F --> G[(tabs)]
    F --> H[modal]
    G --> I[TabLayout]
    I --> J[index]
    I --> K[explore]
    J --> L[HomeScreen]
    L --> M[Screen]
    M --> N[LoginForm]
    N --> O[TextField]
    N --> P[Button]
    L --> Q[SNSButtons]
    Q --> P
```

### Data Flow
The application follows a unidirectional data flow pattern:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    User[User Interaction] --> Component[UI Component]
    Component --> Handler[Event Handler]
    Handler --> State[Component State/MobX]
    State --> Update[State Update]
    Update --> Re-render[Component Re-render]
    Re-render --> UI[Updated UI]
    State --> Service[API/Service Layer]
    Service --> Backend[(Backend API)]
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- **Root Layout**: `/src/app/_layout.tsx` - Main application entry point that determines whether to render Storybook or the main app
- **Tabs Layout**: `/src/app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx` - Defines the tab-based navigation structure
- **Home Screen**: `/src/app/(tabs)/index.tsx` - Primary screen of the application

### Core Modules
- **Theme System**: `/components/provider/ThemeProvider/ThemeProvider.tsx` - Manages light/dark mode with CSS variable integration
- **State Management**: Utilizes MobX through `mobx` and `mobx-react-lite` for reactive state
- **Component Library**: Comprehensive UI components in `/components/ui/` directory
- **Authentication Flow**: Login screen and form components with SNS integration

### Configuration Approach
- **TypeScript**: Configured with path aliases (`@/*`) for easier imports
- **Expo**: Extensive configuration in `app.json` including platform-specific settings
- **Routing**: Expo Router with file-based routing and typed routes enabled
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS integration with `uniwind` and CSS variables

### External Dependencies
- **Core Framework**: Expo 54, React 19, React Native 0.81
- **Navigation**: Expo Router, React Navigation
- **UI Components**: `heroui-native` as the base component library
- **State Management**: MobX ecosystem
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS, uniwind, tailwind-variants
- **Utilities**: lodash-es, @react-native-async-storage/async-storage

### Integration Points
- **SNS Authentication**: Google, Apple, and Kakao login buttons
- **Cross-platform Support**: Web, iOS, and Android with platform-specific code
- **Storybook Integration**: Component development environment with on-device addons
- **Accessibility**: React Native accessibility features through Expo

### Component Relationships
```mermaid
graph LR
    RootLayout --> Providers
    Providers --> ThemeProvider
    RootLayout --> AppLayout
    AppLayout --> StackRouter
    StackRouter --> TabsLayout
    TabsLayout --> HomeScreen
    HomeScreen --> Screen
    Screen --> LoginForm
    Screen --> SNSButtons
    LoginForm --> TextField
    LoginForm --> Button
    SNSButtons --> Button
    ThemeProvider --> UIComponents
    UIComponents --> Button
    UIComponents --> TextField
    UIComponents --> Card
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
The application provides a foundation for a fitness class management system with:

- User authentication through traditional login and SNS providers
- Responsive UI with dark mode support
- Cross-platform compatibility
- Component-driven development with Storybook
- Modern React patterns with Expo Router

### Implementation Highlights
- **Dynamic Theme Switching**: CSS variable-based theming that works across web and native platforms
- **MobX State Management**: Reactive state for login forms and other interactive components
- **Compound Components**: Enhanced Button component that supports start/end icons
- **Conditional Rendering**: SNS buttons can be individually toggled on/off
- **Accessibility**: Proper semantic structure and platform-specific adaptations

### Feature Architecture
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> AppInitialized
    AppInitialized --> ThemeDetection: Detect system preference
    ThemeDetection --> ThemeApplied: Apply light/dark theme
    ThemeApplied --> Routing: Initialize router
    Routing --> HomeScreen: Render home tab
    HomeScreen --> LoginFlow: User interaction
    LoginFlow --> TraditionalLogin: Email/password
    LoginFlow --> SNSLogin: Google/Apple/Kakao
    TraditionalLogin --> FormValidation
    SNSLogin --> OAuthFlow
    FormValidation --> AuthenticationSuccess
    OAuthFlow --> AuthenticationSuccess
    AuthenticationSuccess --> Dashboard
    AuthenticationSuccess --> ErrorState
```

# Welcome to your Expo app 👋

This is an [Expo](https://expo.dev) project created with [`create-expo-app`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/create-expo-app).

## Get started

1. Install dependencies

   ```bash
   npm install
   ```

2. Start the app

   ```bash
   npx expo start
   ```

In the output, you'll find options to open the app in a

- [development build](https://docs.expo.dev/develop/development-builds/introduction/)
- [Android emulator](https://docs.expo.dev/workflow/android-studio-emulator/)
- [iOS simulator](https://docs.expo.dev/workflow/ios-simulator/)
- [Expo Go](https://expo.dev/go), a limited sandbox for trying out app development with Expo

You can start developing by editing the files inside the **app** directory. This project uses [file-based routing](https://docs.expo.dev/router/introduction).

## Get a fresh project

When you're ready, run:

```bash
npm run reset-project
```

This command will move the starter code to the **app-example** directory and create a blank **app** directory where you can start developing.

## Learn more

To learn more about developing your project with Expo, look at the following resources:

- [Expo documentation](https://docs.expo.dev/): Learn fundamentals, or go into advanced topics with our [guides](https://docs.expo.dev/guides).
- [Learn Expo tutorial](https://docs.expo.dev/tutorial/introduction/): Follow a step-by-step tutorial where you'll create a project that runs on Android, iOS, and the web.

## Join the community

Join our community of developers creating universal apps.

- [Expo on GitHub](https://github.com/expo/expo): View our open source platform and contribute.
- [Discord community](https://chat.expo.dev): Chat with Expo users and ask questions.
